               </msIdentifier>
               <msContents>
                  <summary>Record of over 1200 transactions kept by an individual thought to have been a farm manager or steward.  Among the payments listed are those to herdsmen, builders, laborers, watchmen, tax collectors, and craftsmen, and some purchases of goods such as clothing and medicine.  (Goodspeed 1902)</summary>
                  <msItemStruct>
                     <note type="general">Bar code: 68652877.  Based on the months named in the text, the time covered by the accounts is roughly October 191 - April 192 A.D.  The method of accounting in this text resembles double-entry bookkeeping, where there is a credit corresponding to every item debited.  See, for example, col. 17, lines 7-25.  The separate alignment of receipts and expenditures within the same column is an unusual accounting device.  On the whole, the impression produced is of the manager of an estate, whose income is derived from rents and sales, while his expenditures are for building, labor, and the various commodities required for the maintenance of a household.  (Goodspeed 1902, 31-4)</note>
                     <note type="general">Location: Regenstein</note>
                     <note type="general">Image arrangement: abcdef</note>
                     <note type="general">Pub. status: Published: recto and verso</note>
                     <textLang mainLang="grc">Greek</textLang>
                  </msItemStruct>
               </msContents>
